title: Differential cross sections at 0 degree and angular distributions of resolved neutrons from 11B + d

x4codes.hlp: Rice University, Houston, TX, United States of America

x4freetext: One target was made by evaporating natural boron from a
tantalum strip onto a tantalum backing which was 1.9 cm
diam. and 0.13 cm thick.
The other target was an electromagnetically separated
target of 11B  obtained from theAtomic Energy Research
Establishment, Harwell, England. The 11B was deposited
on a 2x2 cm tantalum backing that was 0.013 cm thick.
The thickness of the natural boron target was
determined to be 275+-50 mu-g/cm**2 and the 11B
(Harwell) target to be 187+-34 mu-g/cm**2.
Total error
For neutrons. A single Argon-CO2 filled
proportional dE/dx counter was used between the
radiator and a thin-crystal proportional counter.
Radialors were used of three three different
thicknesses: in the 1-5 MeV deuteron range, 15 mg/cm2
to 45 cm2 thick and above 5 MeV, 30 mg/cm2 to
60 mg/cm2). In order to resolve four neutron groups
(n0 to n3) two radiators were used at given energy
and angle.
For deuterons. 0.25 cm thick, 2.5 cm in diam.,
coved on the sides and in front face with 0.0013 cm
thick Al foil.
